Use conditional compilation or the `MAUI` platform-specific folders pattern. The cleanest approach:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.NotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.NotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.NotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

Each implementation lives in its respective `Platforms/<OS>/` folder and is only compiled for that target, so there's no runtime resolution failure.

**Alternative** — use partial classes with a shared interface and platform files:

```
Services/NotificationService.cs          // shared partial (implements interface)
Platforms/Android/NotificationService.cs  // Android partial
Platforms/iOS/NotificationService.cs      // iOS partial
Platforms/Windows/NotificationService.cs  // Windows partial
```

Then register once without `#if`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, NotificationService>();
```

The `.csproj` already restricts each `Platforms/<OS>/` folder to its target framework, so it compiles cleanly on all platforms.
